{"title_page": "Derek Owusu", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Derek Owusu\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1988}}\n| birth_place   = [[London]], England\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Writer and podcaster\n| language      = English\n| nationality   = British\n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = ''Safe: On Black British Men Reclaiming Space'' (2019)\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     =\n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = {{website|https://derekowusu.com/media}}\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n'''Derek Owusu''' (born 1988)<ref name=Sethi /> is a British writer and podcaster.<ref name=\"metro.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/03/13/black-british-men-talk-about-sexuality-mental-health-culture-and-racism-in-new-book-safe-8889457/|title=Black British men are reclaiming space in new book Safe|first=Faima|last=Bakar|date=13 March 2019|newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]}}</ref> He edited and contributed to the book ''Safe: On Black British Men Reclaiming Space'' (2019); his debut novel is ''That Reminds Me'' (2019).\n\n==Life and work==\nOwusu, of [[Ghanaians in the United Kingdom|Ghanaian heritage]],<ref name=\"buzzfeed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/adeonibada/safe-black-british-men-publishing-industry|title=These Black Male Writers Have Something To Say. Are We Ready To Listen?|first=Ade|last=Onibada|website=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=9 March 2019}}</ref> was raised in [[foster care]] by a white family in a village in [[Suffolk]] until he was eight years old.<ref name=\"mediadiversified\">{{cite web|accessdate=27 May 2019|title=Foster families who ignore race are participating in a pernicious form of racism|url=https://mediadiversified.org/2018/03/02/foster-families-who-ignore-race-are-participating-in-a-pernicious-form-of-racism/|date=2 March 2018|website=[[Media Diversified]]|first=Derek |last=Owusu\n}}</ref> In 1997 he moved from Suffolk to [[North London]] to live with his biological parents.<ref name=\"buzzfeed\"/><ref name=\"mediadiversified\"/>\n\nHe is the former co-host of the literature podcast ''Mostly Lit''.<ref name=\"metro.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"newstatesman.com\"/> <ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/02/we-re-midst-black-british-creative-renaissance-so-where-are-all-black-male-authors-0|first=Yomi|last=Adegoke|authorlink=|title=We\u2019re in the midst of a black British creative renaissance. So where are all the black male authors?|website=[[New Statesman]]|date=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOwusu edited the book ''Safe: On Black British Men Reclaiming Space'' (2019), an anthology of writing by 20 [[Black British]] men.<ref name=\"buzzfeed\"/> He has said that the idea was given to him by fellow writer [[Yomi Adegoke]], who with [[Elizabeth Uviebinen\u00e9]] had compiled the book called ''Slay In Your Lane'' and suggested that something similar from a male perspective would be a good idea.<ref>Sinclair, Leah (26 June 2019), [https://www.voice-online.co.uk/entertainment/books/2019/06/26/black-male-britons-reclaim-their-space-in-new-book/ \"Black Male Britons Reclaim Their Space In New Book\"], ''[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]''.</ref> It includes essays by [[JJ Bola]], [[Suli Breaks]], [[Alex Wheatle]], [[Courttia Newland]] and others<ref name=\"metro.co.uk\"/><ref>[https://rsliterature.org/rsl-event/members-book-group-safe-ed-by-derek-owusu/ \"Members' Book Group \u2013 Safe ed. by Derek Owusu\"], [[Royal Society of Literature]], 12 November 2019.</ref> that are, as Alex Mistlin wrote in ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]],'' \"addressing the conflicts and complexities of being a black man in Britain today\".<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/bjqywa/safe-depicts-black-british-masculinity-in-all-its-glory|title='SAFE' Depicts Black British Masculinity in All Its Glory|first1=Alex|last1=Mistlin|first2=Emma|last2=Garland|date=1 March 2019|work=Vice}}</ref> According to Mistlin, ''Safe'' is \"about the multi-faceted nature of the black experience, how blackness intertwines with society, masculinity and sexuality to form a coherent identity that is at once universal and unique.\"<ref name=\"vice\"/> Owusu contributes an essay about his experience of foster care.<ref name=\"buzzfeed\"/><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=27 May 2019|title=\u2018Throw masculinity away\u2019 \u2013 author Derek Owusu on why black British men needed a space like Safe|url=http://gal-dem.com/throw-masculinity-away-author-derek-owusu-on-being-a-black-british-man/|date=25 April 2019|website=[[gal-dem]]|first=Kemi |last=Alemoru}}</ref><ref>Biswas, K. (12 June 2019), [https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/books/2019/06/how-black-culture-went-mainstream \"How black culture went mainstream\"], ''New Statesman''.</ref>\n\nOwusu's coming-of-age debut novel, ''That Reminds Me'', was published in 2019, the first novel from [[Stormzy]]'s imprint #Merky Books.<ref>Wood, Heloise (18 July 2019), [https://www.thebookseller.com/news/merky-books-buys-two-books-mostly-lits-derek-owusu-1040191 \"Mostly Lit's Derek Owusu signs two-book deal with Stormzy imprint\"], ''[[The Bookseller]]''.</ref><ref name=\"guardian-donkor\">{{cite news|first1=Michael|last1=Donkor|authorlink=Michael Donkor|accessdate=1 December 2019|title=That Reminds Me by Derek Owusu review \u2013 a fresh and powerful debut|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/nov/21/that-reminds-me-derek-owusu-review|newspaper=The Guardian|date=21 November 2019|issn=0261-3077|via=}}</ref> According to ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]],'' \"there\u2019s nothing indulgent about this quietly observed account of a black man Owusu gives the name of K, who is struggling to make sense of a chaotic upbringing and of his place in a world not designed for people like him with a hidden mental health problem.\" [[Kate Kellaway]], poetry critic for ''[[The Observer]],'' picking ''That Reminds Me'' as her poetry book of the month for November, called it \"brave and moving\", describing it as \"semi-autobiographical\", as both K, the protagonist, and Owusu himself live with a diagnosis of [[borderline personality disorder]].<ref name=Sethi>{{cite web|accessdate=25 November 2019|title=Derek Owusu: 'Mental health issues that people find scary aren\u2019t being talked about'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/nov/02/derek-owusu-that-reminds-me-stormzy-mens-mental-health|date=2 November 2019|website=The Guardian|first=Anita |last=Sethi|authorlink=Anita Sethi}}</ref><ref>Allfree, Claire (17 November 2019), [https://www.metro.news/book-reviews-thanks-to-stormzy-heres-a-poetic-memoir-of-life-as-a-black-man/1800966/ \"Book reviews: Thanks to Stormzy, here\u2019s a poetic memoir of life as a black man\"], ''Metro''.</ref><ref name=Kellaway>{{cite web|accessdate=9 December 2019|title=That Reminds Me by Derek Owusu review \u2013 defies categorisation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/nov/26/derek-owusu-that-reminds-me-review-poetry-book-of-the-month|date=26 November 2019|website=The Observer|first=Kate |last=Kellaway}}</ref> It was described by ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] ''as a \"virtuosic debut by a raw new talent\".<ref name=Cooper>{{cite web|accessdate=26 December 2019|url=https://www.pressreader.com/search?query=derek%20owusu&newspapers=1130&start=2019-12-19&stop=2019-12-19&hideSimilar=1&type=3&state=4|title=That Reminds Me by Derek Owusu: A virtuosic debut by a raw new talent| date=19 December 2019|website=The Herald Digital|first=Neil|last=Cooper}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n===Fiction===\n*''That Reminds Me.'' London: Merky, 2019. {{ISBN|978-1529118599}}.<ref name=\"guardian-donkor\"/>\n\n===As editor===\n*''Safe: On Black British Men Reclaiming Space''. London: Trapeze, 2019. {{ISBN|978-1409182634}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/life-culture/article/42995/1/lgbtq-books-2019-andea-lawlor-niven-govinden-tom-rasmussen-juno-dawson|title=11 new LGBTQ books to read in 2019|first=Salma|last=Haidrani|date=21 January 2019|website=Dazed}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://derekowusu.com/home Derek Owusu poetry website]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/27/white-privilege-is-used-by-women-against-black-men-as-a-tool-of-oppression \"\u2018I had to submit to being exoticised by white women. If I didn\u2019t, I was punished\u2019\"].  Extract from ''Safe'' by Courttia Newland\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/mar/06/father-figures-why-the-new-wave-of-visible-black-dads-give-me-hope \"Father figures: why the new wave of visible black dads gives me hope\"]. Extract from ''Safe'' by [[Joseph Harker]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cZf6X4mkIug \"SAFE edited by Derek Owusu\"], Waterstones, 6 March 2019. YouTube video.\n* [https://ownit.london/derek-owusu/ \"Derek Owusu\"] at Own It! \n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owusu, Derek}}\n\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Ghanaian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:People with borderline personality disorder]]\n[[Category:Black British writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Derek Owusu\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1988}}\n| birth_place   = [[London]], England\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Writer and podcaster\n| language      = \n| nationality   = British\n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = ''Safe: On Black British Men Reclaiming Space'' (2019)\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     =\n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = {{website|https://derekowusu.com/media}}\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n'''Derek Owusu''' (born 1988)<ref name=Sethi /> is a British writer and podcaster.<ref name=\"metro.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/03/13/black-british-men-talk-about-sexuality-mental-health-culture-and-racism-in-new-book-safe-8889457/|title=Black British men are reclaiming space in new book Safe|first=Faima|last=Bakar|date=13 March 2019|newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]}}</ref> He edited and contributed to the book ''Safe: On Black British Men Reclaiming Space'' (2019); his debut novel is ''That Reminds Me'' (2019).\n\n==Life and work==\nOwusu, of [[Ghanaians in the United Kingdom|Ghanaian heritage]],<ref name=\"buzzfeed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/adeonibada/safe-black-british-men-publishing-industry|title=These Black Male Writers Have Something To Say. Are We Ready To Listen?|first=Ade|last=Onibada|website=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=9 March 2019}}</ref> was raised in [[foster care]] by a white family in a village in [[Suffolk]] until he was eight years old.<ref name=\"mediadiversified\">{{cite web|accessdate=27 May 2019|title=Foster families who ignore race are participating in a pernicious form of racism|url=https://mediadiversified.org/2018/03/02/foster-families-who-ignore-race-are-participating-in-a-pernicious-form-of-racism/|date=2 March 2018|website=[[Media Diversified]]|first=Derek |last=Owusu\n}}</ref> In 1997 he moved from Suffolk to [[North London]] to live with his biological parents.<ref name=\"buzzfeed\"/><ref name=\"mediadiversified\"/>\n\nHe is the former co-host of the literature podcast ''Mostly Lit''<ref name=\"metro.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"newstatesman.com\"/> <ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/2019/02/we-re-midst-black-british-creative-renaissance-so-where-are-all-black-male-authors-0|first=Yomi|last=Adegoke|authorlink=|title=We\u2019re in the midst of a black British creative renaissance. So where are all the black male authors?|website=[[New Statesman]]|date=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOwusu edited the book ''Safe: On Black British Men Reclaiming Space'' (2019), an anthology of writing by 20 [[Black British]] men.<ref name=\"buzzfeed\"/> He has said that the idea was given to him by fellow writer [[Yomi Adegoke]], who with [[Elizabeth Uviebinen\u00e9]] had compiled the book called ''Slay In Your Lane'' and suggested that something similar from a male perspective would be a good idea.<ref>Sinclair, Leah (26 June 2019), [https://www.voice-online.co.uk/entertainment/books/2019/06/26/black-male-britons-reclaim-their-space-in-new-book/ \"Black Male Britons Reclaim Their Space In New Book\"], ''[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]''.</ref> It includes essays by [[JJ Bola]], [[Suli Breaks]], [[Alex Wheatle]], [[Courttia Newland]] and others<ref name=\"metro.co.uk\"/><ref>[https://rsliterature.org/rsl-event/members-book-group-safe-ed-by-derek-owusu/ \"Members' Book Group \u2013 Safe ed. by Derek Owusu\"], [[Royal Society of Literature]], 12 November 2019.</ref> that are, as Alex Mistlin wrote in ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]],'' \"addressing the conflicts and complexities of being a black man in Britain today\".<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/bjqywa/safe-depicts-black-british-masculinity-in-all-its-glory|title='SAFE' Depicts Black British Masculinity in All Its Glory|first1=Alex|last1=Mistlin|first2=Emma|last2=Garland|date=1 March 2019|work=Vice}}</ref> According to Mistlin, ''Safe'' is \"about the multi-faceted nature of the black experience, how blackness intertwines with society, masculinity and sexuality to form a coherent identity that is at once universal and unique.\"<ref name=\"vice\"/> Owusu contributes an essay about his experience of foster care.<ref name=\"buzzfeed\"/><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=27 May 2019|title=\u2018Throw masculinity away\u2019 \u2013 author Derek Owusu on why black British men needed a space like Safe|url=http://gal-dem.com/throw-masculinity-away-author-derek-owusu-on-being-a-black-british-man/|date=25 April 2019|website=[[gal-dem]]|first=Kemi |last=Alemoru}}</ref><ref>Biswas, K. (12 June 2019), [https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/books/2019/06/how-black-culture-went-mainstream \"How black culture went mainstream\"], ''New Statesman''.</ref>\n\nOwusu's coming-of-age debut novel, ''That Reminds Me'', was published in 2019, the first novel from [[Stormzy]]'s imprint #Merky Books.<ref>Wood, Heloise (18 July 2019), [https://www.thebookseller.com/news/merky-books-buys-two-books-mostly-lits-derek-owusu-1040191 \"Mostly Lit's Derek Owusu signs two-book deal with Stormzy imprint\"], ''[[The Bookseller]]''.</ref><ref name=\"guardian-donkor\">{{cite news|first1=Michael|last1=Donkor|authorlink=Michael Donkor|accessdate=1 December 2019|title=That Reminds Me by Derek Owusu review \u2013 a fresh and powerful debut|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/nov/21/that-reminds-me-derek-owusu-review|newspaper=The Guardian|date=21 November 2019|issn=0261-3077|via=}}</ref> According to ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]],'' \"there\u2019s nothing indulgent about this quietly observed account of a black man Owusu gives the name of K, who is struggling to make sense of a chaotic upbringing and of his place in a world not designed for people like him with a hidden mental health problem.\" [[Kate Kellaway]], poetry critic for ''[[The Observer]],'' picking ''That Reminds Me'' as her poetry book of the month for November, called it \"brave and moving\", describing it as \"semi-autobiographical\", as both K, the protagonist, and Owusu himself live with a diagnosis of [[borderline personality disorder]].<ref name=Sethi>{{cite web|accessdate=25 November 2019|title=Derek Owusu: 'Mental health issues that people find scary aren\u2019t being talked about'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/nov/02/derek-owusu-that-reminds-me-stormzy-mens-mental-health|date=2 November 2019|website=The Guardian|first=Anita |last=Sethi|authorlink=Anita Sethi}}</ref><ref>Allfree, Claire (17 November 2019), [https://www.metro.news/book-reviews-thanks-to-stormzy-heres-a-poetic-memoir-of-life-as-a-black-man/1800966/ \"Book reviews: Thanks to Stormzy, here\u2019s a poetic memoir of life as a black man\"], ''Metro''.</ref><ref name=Kellaway>{{cite web|accessdate=9 December 2019|title=That Reminds Me by Derek Owusu review \u2013 defies categorisation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/nov/26/derek-owusu-that-reminds-me-review-poetry-book-of-the-month|date=26 November 2019|website=The Guardian|first=Kate |last=Kellaway}}</ref> It was described by ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] ''as a \"virtuosic debut by a raw new talent\".<ref name=Cooper>{{cite web|accessdate=26 December 2019|url=https://www.pressreader.com/search?query=derek%20owusu&newspapers=1130&start=2019-12-19&stop=2019-12-19&hideSimilar=1&type=3&state=4|title=That Reminds Me by Derek Owusu: A virtuosic debut by a raw new talent| date=19 December 2019|website=The Herald Digital|first=Neil|last=Cooper}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n===Fiction===\n*''That Reminds Me.'' London: Merky, 2019. {{ISBN|978-1529118599}}.<ref name=\"guardian-donkor\"/>\n\n===As editor===\n*''Safe: On Black British Men Reclaiming Space''. London: Trapeze, 2019. {{ISBN|978-1409182634}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/life-culture/article/42995/1/lgbtq-books-2019-andea-lawlor-niven-govinden-tom-rasmussen-juno-dawson|title=11 new LGBTQ books to read in 2019|first=Salma|last=Haidrani|date=21 January 2019|website=Dazed}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://derekowusu.com/home Derek Owusu poetry website]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/27/white-privilege-is-used-by-women-against-black-men-as-a-tool-of-oppression \"\u2018I had to submit to being exoticised by white women. If I didn\u2019t, I was punished\u2019\"].  Extract from ''Safe'' by Courttia Newland\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/mar/06/father-figures-why-the-new-wave-of-visible-black-dads-give-me-hope \"Father figures: why the new wave of visible black dads gives me hope\"]. Extract from ''Safe'' by [[Joseph Harker]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cZf6X4mkIug \"SAFE edited by Derek Owusu\"], Waterstones, 6 March 2019. YouTube video.\n* [https://ownit.london/derek-owusu/ \"Derek Owusu\"] at Own It! \n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owusu, Derek}}\n\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Ghanaian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:People with borderline personality disorder]]\n[[Category:Black British writers]]\n", "name_user": "Proscribe", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derek_Owusu"}
